> +			 "/proc/%d/ns/pid_for_children", parent_pid);
> +		nsfd = open(path, O_RDONLY);
> +		ASSERT_GE(nsfd, 0);
> +
> +		ASSERT_EQ(0, setns(nsfd, CLONE_NEWPID));
[ ... ]
> +	close(pipe_fd[0]);
> +
> +	if (geteuid())
> +		ASSERT_EQ(0, unshare(CLONE_NEWUSER));

Will this test fail when run as an unprivileged user?

Because the child is forked before the parent calls unshare(CLONE_NEWUSER),
the child remains in the initial user namespace without elevated capabilities.

When the parent unshares its user namespace, its dumpable flag is cleared.
Does this cause the child's attempt to open the parent's pid_for_children
symlink to fail with -EACCES, since the child lacks CAP_SYS_PTRACE?

Additionally, if the file descriptor could be opened, wouldn't the subsequent
setns() call fail with -EPERM because the child lacks CAP_SYS_ADMIN in its
current user namespace?

The second test case (pidns_init_via_setns_set_tid) appears to avoid this by
entering the new user namespace before forking the descendant processes.

> +
> +	ASSERT_EQ(0, unshare(CLONE_NEWPID));
> +
> +	/* Signal child that the new PID namespace is ready */
> +	buf = 0;

